The data is from 51490 games from a game called League of Legends. Even though there are more than 61 variables, most of them have similar attributes (For example t1_ban1, t1_ban2 and t1_ban3 are variables that ban a certain character in that order).

This dataset was collected using the Riot Games API, which makes it easy to lookup and collect information on a users ranked history and collect their games.

Purpose of the explanatory analysis

It is always crucial to have a goal in mind when doing data analysis, so for this assignment, we will focus on how to successfully predict whether a team wins.

Cleaning and preprocessing data

-Converting the variables into the right types -Changing 1 and 2 into team 1 and team 2 when necessary -Drop columns that are not relevant for this assignment -Some columns can be removed using domain knowledge. For instance, selecting spells is often a fixed procedure so it wont fluctate the overall win ratio.

###Converting the variables into the right types
myData <- myData %>% mutate_at(vars(4:ncol(myData)), as.character)

###Replace 1 and 2 with team 1 and team 2
myData <- myData %>% mutate(winner = replace(winner, winner ==1,"team 1"),
                  firstBlood = replace(firstBlood, firstBlood ==1,"team 1"),
                  firstTower = replace(firstTower, firstTower ==1,"team 1"),
                  firstInhibitor = replace(firstInhibitor, firstInhibitor ==1,"team 1"),
                  firstBaron = replace(firstBaron, firstBaron ==1,"team 1"), 
                  firstDragon = replace(firstDragon, firstDragon ==1,"team 1"),
                  winner = replace(winner, winner ==2,"team 2"),
                  firstBlood = replace(firstBlood, firstBlood ==2,"team 2"),
                  firstTower = replace(firstTower, firstTower ==2,"team 2"),
                  firstInhibitor = replace(firstInhibitor, firstInhibitor ==2,"team 2"),
                  firstBaron = replace(firstBaron, firstBaron ==2,"team 2"), 
                  firstDragon = replace(firstDragon, firstDragon ==2,"team 2"))

###Dropping unncessary column(s)
myData <- myData %>% select(-c(2, 4, 13, 14, 16, 17, 19, 20, 22, 23, 25, 26, 31:36, 38, 39, 41, 42, 44, 45, 47, 48, 50, 51, 56:61))

So lets do some analysis on the data

First of all, lets see the win rate of the teams: Team 1 is blue side, while team 2 is red side. Looking at the graph, it seems like team 1 has won more games, but not by a huge margin.

ggplot(data = myData, aes(x = winner, fill = winner)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

winners <- myData %>%
  count(winner) %>%
  mutate(winPercentage = prop.table(n))
winners
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   winner     n winPercentage

## 1 team 1 26077         0.506
## 2 team 2 25413         0.494

The table shows that the winning percentage has around 1% difference, this means that on a specific side wont win you more games.

Next, lets see the impact of taking the first turret of the game

ggplot(data = myData, aes(x = firstTower, fill = winner)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

It seems like taking turret has quite an impact on winning the game. Though, it makes sense since it is a rare case that a losing team takes first turret, so the team already has an advantage before taking the turret.

The 0 turret means an early surrender, this means that someone didnt properly connect to the game and the game is disbanded.

Next, lets see if the characters have a different win ratio. But before we analyze it, we need to transform the dataset since the crucial information isnt shown on the original data like black and white.

First of all, we divide the dataset into team 1 and team 2 with their corresponding characters for each match. Also, we assign the result of the match with the corresponding row.

Then, we combine the two datasets and group the characters with the same ID so we can see how many times the character lost or won. Finally, dividing the number of times the character won by the total times played, we have the winning percentage of the characters.

team1Win <- myData %>% 
  ###Get the players of the team and which team won for team 1
  select(winner, t1_champ1id, t1_champ2id, t1_champ3id, t1_champ4id, t1_champ5id) %>% 
  ###Change the variable to whether the team won or lost
  mutate(winner = case_when(winner == "team 1"~ 1, 
                            winner == "team 2" ~ 0, 
                            TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  ###Rename the variables so we can combine rows later
  rename(champ1id = t1_champ1id, champ2id = t1_champ2id, champ3id = t1_champ3id, champ4id = t1_champ4id, champ5id = t1_champ5id)


team2Win <- myData %>% 
  ###Get the players of the team and which team won for team 2
  select(winner, t2_champ1id, t2_champ2id, t2_champ3id, t2_champ4id, t2_champ5id) %>% 
  ###Change the variable to whether the team won or lost
  mutate(winner = case_when(winner == "team 1"~ 0, 
                            winner == "team 2" ~ 1, 
                            TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  ###Rename the variables so we can combine rows later
  rename(champ1id = t2_champ1id, champ2id = t2_champ2id, champ3id = t2_champ3id, champ4id = t2_champ4id, champ5id = t2_champ5id)

champWin <- bind_rows(team1Win, team2Win)



###Get frequency
champStats <- champWin %>% 
  group_by(champ1id, winner) %>%
  tally() %>%
  ###Get the total number of games played for each character
  group_by(champ1id) %>%
  mutate(total = sum(n))%>%
  ###Get the winning percentage
  mutate(percentage = n/total * 100) %>% 
  filter(winner == 1) %>%
  mutate(totalMean = case_when(total>746 ~1,
                               total<=746~0,
                               TRUE ~2)) %>% 
  mutate_at(6, as.character)
  
ggplot(data = champStats, aes(x = champ1id, y = percentage, colour = totalMean)) + geom_point()

As the results show, there is a relatively huge difference between the characters, with the lowest less than 40% and the highest above 56%. So we need to keep this variable in mind when creating a prediction model.

Do characters that occur more frequently have a higher percentage of winning the game? (0 = smaller than the mean, 1 = greater than the mean) Looking at the graph, I doubt it.

Now lets see how much of an impact first blood has on the game. First blood means the first team killing an enemy character

ggplot(data = myData, aes(x = firstBlood, fill = winner)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

Even though first blood gives a team an advantage, it seems like it isnt big enough to get a greater lead than people think. One of the reasons I can think of is due to the fact that the game has implemented some elements that stop games from snowballing, so teams are able to come back even when they are sightly behind.

Though, the correlation test gives us the following:

test <- chisq.test(myData$winner, myData$firstBlood)

So we will have to take a closer look at this variable.

In this game, an objective called Baron increases the power of the team that takes it. Lets see how this objective improves the chance of winning:

ggplot(myData, aes(x =gameDuration, y = t1_baronKills , colour = winner)) +geom_jitter() + 
  scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

ggplot(myData, aes(x =gameDuration, y = t2_baronKills , colour = winner)) +geom_jitter() + 
  scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

As expected, both team 1 and team 2 have similar results. At 0 barons, both teams depend on other variables to win instead of the baron. It gets interesting however, at 1 or more barons. Both graphs shows that taking barons will increase the chance of winning the game, especially at the early stages. However, the longer the game gets dragged, the higher the chance that the advantage fades away and the opposite team steals some games. At three barons, it is unpredictable who is going to be on top. My assumption on this is because both teams get more than one baron in this case and a lot of fighting is going on that has not much to do with winning the game. This is also referred as Clown fiesta.

So according to this graph, taking barons will increase the chance of winning, but you also need to end as soon as possible before the opposite team catches up.

Next, we are going to make a prediction on which team wins based on the variables in the dataset.

At first, I wanted to use random forest, but since there are too many categorical variables, R needs to calculate 2^{1447 - 1} - 1 splits, which is computational too heavy for Random forest in R.

By using multinomial logistic regression, we can set the max weight in the parameter to prevent the model not able to handle all the weights. Even though it makes sense not to do it with a small dataset because nothing sensible will come out with only a limited observation. However, with more than 50k observations (And more than 30k in training set) it is worth a try to see how well the model predicts.
